{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cf7a4618-63d2-4967-ab7f-90fbe439ebe4","content":"Your tutorial is **partially correct** but has an issue with the second property.\n\n### ✅ `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` — Correct\n\nThis is the right approach in .NET MAUI (including .NET 10). You need the iOS platform-specific namespace:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\nThis automatically insets your page content to avoid the notch/Dynamic Island.\n\n### ❌ `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` — Not a real MAUI property\n\nThere is **no `IgnoreSafeArea` property** on `Grid` or any layout in .NET MAUI. Your tutorial may be confusing this with SwiftUI's `.ignoresSafeArea()` or a third-party API.\n\n### How to do a full-bleed background image\n\nInstead, **don't set `UseSafeArea`** on the page, and manually pad your content:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\">\n    <Grid>\n        <!-- Background image fills full screen, behind notch -->\n        <Image Source=\"bg.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n\n        <!-- Content respects safe area via padding -->\n        <Grid ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n            <Label Text=\"Hello, safe area!\" />\n        </Grid>\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nOr, if most of your app uses safe areas, keep `UseSafeArea=\"True\"` on the page and use negative margins or a custom handler to let specific elements bleed out.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"638e340d-77e1-4f21-9971-8578ed7afc8c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository doesn't seem to have any content related to safe area APIs. Let me answer based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI safe area handling.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the safe area APIs have evolved:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` — This is the **old Xamarin.Forms** approach using platform-specifics (`Xamarin.Forms.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific`). In .NET MAUI, this was carried forward but the API changed. In .NET MAUI, it's still available as `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` with the namespace `xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"`.\n\n\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea` — This isn't a standard .NET MAUI property, and it wasn't in Xamarin.Forms either. I need to reconsider what safe area properties are actually available in .NET MAUI.\n\nFor .NET 10 specifically, I should account for the fact that it's still in preview. There were some safe area handling improvements in .NET 9, and the recommended approach remains using `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`. The `IgnoreSafeArea` property the user's tutorial mentions doesn't exist as a built-in MAUI property on layouts — it might be from a third-party library or possibly confused with something from another framework like SwiftUI.\n\nLet me clarify what actually works: `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` is the correct MAUI approach, requiring the iOS-specific namespace. But `IgnoreSafeArea` on Grid isn't standard MAUI. If you need a background to extend behind the safe area, you'd skip using `UseSafeArea` on the page instead.","outputTokens":1251,"requestId":"1121:31275C:CF9E0D:F1E7AD:69FE8957"},"id":"f0949c3e-fdd8-44cb-a9cf-edcdf95b410c","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:10:08.724Z","parentId":"1f841f4e-ffec-48b8-9a8e-86c1514222d6"}
